// TEST: exec_match_exprpos_let_typed
// EXPECT: output "stop;slow;go"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Expression-position `match` bound into a typed `let` whose declared type
// differs from the enclosing function's return type (Q-match-exprpos,
// codegen-completeness P4): `let a: Action = match l { … }` inside a function
// that returns `String`. The match yields a *user-enum* value (`Action`), bound
// into `a: Action`, while `decide` returns `String`.
//
// Go (P4): the expression-position match lowers to an IIFE. Its return type was
// taken from `current_fn_ret_type` (here `string`), so a value-position match
// binding into `Action` emitted `func() string { … }()` — not assignable to the
// `var a Action`. The fix records the binding's declared type as a
// `current_expected_type` around the `let` value emit and prefers it for the
// IIFE return, so the IIFE is `func() Action { … }()`.
//
// TS (P4): the value-position match IIFE arrow is now annotated with the
// binding type (`(() : Action => { … })()`) and a bare-identifier scrutinee is
// hoisted to a temp (`const __matchN = l; switch (__matchN._tag) …`) so the
// `switch` narrows the temp, not the original binding.
//
// Python (P4): an expression-position user-enum match arm test resolved the
// variant through the registry to its `{enum}_{variant}` dataclass
// (`isinstance(__v, Light_Red)`) rather than the bare variant leaf name
// (`isinstance(__v, Red)`, an undefined name) — mirroring the statement-position
// `emit_pattern`.
//
// js/rust already handled this (JS is untyped; Rust binds the enum value
// natively).
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

enum Light {
  Red
  Yellow
  Green
}

enum Action {
  Stop
  Slow
  Go
}

fn decide(l: Light) -> String {
  let a: Action = match l {
    Red => Stop
    Yellow => Slow
    Green => Go
  }
  match a {
    Stop => return "stop"
    Slow => return "slow"
    Go => return "go"
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  println("${decide(Red)};${decide(Yellow)};${decide(Green)}")
}
